"title": "5445: potters and pottery",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "5445: potters and pottery",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>Pottery was in common use for both household and ceremonial utensils, though for sacred use precious metals were often preferred. Broken pottery symbolises worthlessness and judgment. The potter formed clay with his hands on a wheel which he turned with his feet. The descriptions of God as a potter and of his people as clay emphasise God's sovereignty and also his concern for what he has made.</p>\n<h2>Potters in Scripture</h2>\n<h3>Examples of potters</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer18:2\">JER 18:2</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Chr4:23\">1CH 4:23</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer19:1\">JER 19:1</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Zech11:13\">ZEC 11:13</a> <em>Potters may have been associated with the temple, possibly because of the continuing need for new vessels to be used in religious ceremonies</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt27:7\">MAT 27:7</a></p>\n<h3>Description of the potter's work</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Prov26:23\">PRO 26:23</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer18:3-Jer18:4\">JER 18:3–18:4</a></p>\n<h2>God depicted as a potter</h2>\n<h3>God's authority over what he has made</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer18:6\">JER 18:6</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa29:16\">ISA 29:16</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa45:9-Isa45:10\">ISA 45:9–45:10</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom9:20-Rom9:21\">ROM 9:20–9:21</a></p>\n<h3>God's concern for what he has made</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa64:8-Isa64:9\">ISA 64:8–64:9</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen2:7-Gen2:8\">GEN 2:7–2:8</a> <em>“Formed” commonly describes the action of the potter. God “formed” both individuals and the nation</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job10:8-Job10:9\">JOB 10:8–10:9</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps103:14\">PSA 103:14</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps119:73\">PSA 119:73</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa43:1\">ISA 43:1</a></p>\n<h2>Broken pottery</h2>\n<h3>Contaminated pottery to be broken</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev11:33-Lev11:35\">LEV 11:33–11:35</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev15:12\">LEV 15:12</a></p>\n<h3>Broken pottery as a symbol of judgment</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer19:10-Jer19:11\">JER 19:10–19:11</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps2:9\">PSA 2:9</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev2:27\">REV 2:27</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa30:14\">ISA 30:14</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer25:34\">JER 25:34</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer48:12\">JER 48:12</a></p>\n<h3>Broken pottery as a symbol of worthlessness</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps31:12\">PSA 31:12</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer22:28\">JER 22:28</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer19:2\">JER 19:2</a> <em>The Potsherd Gate was so called because it overlooked the dump for broken pottery.</em></p>\n<h2>Pottery of little value</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lam4:2\">LAM 4:2</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps60:8\">PSA 60:8</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps108:9\">PSA 108:9</a><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Cor4:7\">2CO 4:7</a></strong> <em>Valuables were often concealed in apparently worthless clay jars which did not attract attention.</em></p>\n<h2>Examples of items of pottery</h2>\n<p><em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Sam17:28\">2SA 17:28</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Tim2:20\">2TI 2:20</a></p>\n<h3>Cooking pots</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg6:19\">JDG 6:19</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam2:14\">1SA 2:14</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs4:38-2Kgs4:41\">2KI 4:38–4:41</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job41:20\">JOB 41:20</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mic3:3\">MIC 3:3</a></p>\n<h3>Pitchers to carry water</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen24:17-Gen24:20\">GEN 24:17–24:20</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg7:16\">JDG 7:16</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark14:13\">MRK 14:13</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke22:10\">LUK 22:10</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John4:28\">JHN 4:28</a></p>\n<h3>Water jugs</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam26:11-1Sam26:12\">1SA 26:11–26:12</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs17:10\">1KI 17:10</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs19:6\">1KI 19:6</a></p>\n<h3>Drinking vessels</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg5:25\">JDG 5:25</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer35:5\">JER 35:5</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt26:27-Matt26:28\">MAT 26:27–26:28</a> parallels <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark14:23-Mark14:24\">MRK 14:23–14:24</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke22:20\">LUK 22:20</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor11:25\">1CO 11:25</a></p>\n<h3>Other pottery containers</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs14:3\">1KI 14:3</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs4:3-2Kgs4:4\">2KI 4:3–4:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs21:13\">2KI 21:13</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer32:14\">JER 32:14</a> <em>Documents could be kept intact in clay jars for many years</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt26:23\">MAT 26:23</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John13:5\">JHN 13:5</a></p>\n<h3>Household lamps</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs4:10\">2KI 4:10</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt5:15\">MAT 5:15</a></p>\n<h2>Pottery used in religious rituals</h2>\n<h3>Basins to hold the blood of sacrifices</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod12:21-Exod12:22\">EXO 12:21–12:22</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod24:6\">EXO 24:6</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev14:5\">LEV 14:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev14:50\">LEV 14:50</a></p>\n<h3>Utensils to cook or bake offerings</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev6:28\">LEV 6:28</a></strong> <em>The sin offering was cooked in a pot which was then broken.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev2:5\">LEV 2:5</a> <em>The grain offering might be baked on a clay griddle</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev6:21\">LEV 6:21</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev7:9\">LEV 7:9</a></p>\n<h3>Clay water jars</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num5:17\">NUM 5:17</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num19:17\">NUM 19:17</a></p>\n<h3>Lamps</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod25:37\">EXO 25:37</a></strong> <em>A clay lamp was held on each of the golden lampstand's seven branches.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod27:21\">EXO 27:21</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod30:8\">EXO 30:8</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev24:3-Lev24:4\">LEV 24:3–24:4</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam3:3\">1SA 3:3</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs7:49\">1KI 7:49</a></p>",
